The only proven solution so far to Covid-19 lies in discipline and adherence to the simple preventive measures such as face masks, social distancing, hygiene, avoiding crowded places and close human interactions.
But everywhere we look, we see reckless behaviour in the streets, shopping centres, market places, churches, mosques, political rallies and even family gatherings. Covid-19 super-spreader events have become the norm, and will surely continue into the New Year.





There also seems to be no solution in sight to the economic carnage designed by the Jubilee government. President Kenyatta and Deputy President William Ruto were elected into office promising an energy and imagination of youth that would deliver a stable, prosperous and united new Kenya.
‘Borrow, spend and steal’ policies
Instead, we have regressed into utter incompetence and mismanagement, destruction of the economy, and unearthing of the atavistic tribal and political rivalries that always act as sparks to electoral conflagration.
Corruption
Corruption has spiralled out of control despite all the rhetoric, and we can be sure that the ‘borrow, spend and steal’ economic policies will continue to impoverish us all.
Then there is the politics. Whether it is the BBI referendum or premature positioning for 2022, it’s criminal to burden Kenyans with mindless duels at a time when Covid-19 and economic collapse are both taking such terrible tolls.



