Ethnic chiefs
Save for the usual bunch of self-seeking politicians, mercenary cheering squads and self-appointed community elders for hire, nowhere was there a meeting where the Kikuyu community endorsed the alleged power transfer pact.
And neither were the Kalenjin as a community bound, man, woman and child, to support such a private deal. In any case, political pacts of that nature, whether signed on paper or sealed with illegal oaths, are worthless and not binding even to the beneficiaries, leave alone their communities.
State House does not belong to President Kenyatta, and it is not for him to bequeath it to anyone. Neither does it belong to the extended Kikuyu community, which therefore cannot be bound to such promises.
Finally, the argument which is so prevalent in central Kenya falls flat on its face on a basic principle: If President Kenyatta ever had the mandate to bind the entire Kikuyu nation to a political promise, it follows that he also has the mandate to free the people from the alleged debt.
And he would also have the mandate to bind his people to a new arrangement with Mr Odinga or any other succession contender. Balderdash, I repeat.
As we enter the New Year, the best we can do is free ourselves from the baggage of worthless political promises and mindless loyalty to ethnic chiefs.



